author: @SakuraWulf
text: I finished my Google IT Support Professional cert and after looking through job postings for entry level helpdesk roles, I noticed that data analyst pops up almost more than helpdesk, especially on careercircle. I've also been contacted by recruiters regarding my medical background to work in that field. I declined and after letting them know I was interested primarily in IT, they asked what roles specifically. They didn't seem to give much of a response when I said help desk (I'm guessing because it's easier to slot me into a medical role with my background and there are more "qualified" individuals for help desk they can consider) but it sounded like they were more familiar with or looking for Data Analyst roles compared to help desk.  Since the COMPTIA certs are arbitrarily expensive, especially the barrier to entry A+, I'll be going this route. I can't thank you enough for the resources you're offering to people looking to build their skillset in Data Analytics, Alex. I'm diving in.   EDIT: Cloud really isn't that hard to learn if you're tech savvy, if you were on the fence, it's just a lot of information to memorize and companies aren't going to offer you a role as a cloud consultant or architect/engineer without prior experience in IT either way, unless you have a strong reference.

text: Alex, I want to chip in my experience here. I was a Finance graduate, and just like you, have 0 background in data, but I do have a little bit of statistical knowledge coming from an Economics minor. I did all the things you and Luke taught on becoming a data analyst from scratch, all the projects, the portfolio, the courses, the recruiters, EVERYTHING. 3 months of intensive learning and another 3 months of job hunting afterwards, I got myself a job in an islamic finance company, collecting data of unit trust funds around the world and consolidating them into a database, constantly updating them, making analysis on them, finding pattern and trends. author: @DarkGT
text: SQL  is hard, you can learn the basics in 3-4 days no doubts. Doing complicated things with SQL takes a lot more time. Make it 4-5 months min to master SQL only. Excel is tricky too. Some jobs ask for VBA and Excel, takes time to master Excel, let alone knowing the visual basic. Tableau or Power Bi. For my Power Bi certificate I had to reschedule the exam once. I didn't feel ready for it. The exam suggest that is for Junior analyst with 6 month experience. It's expected to have being working with Power Bi for at least that much before you get a professional certificate about it. It took me 4 months for the certificate btw and I barely passed it.  Where you place R or Python in that short time frame? Knowing Python first, then how to work with libraries doing the actual data work, then if you need web scrapping also learning that. Just won't happen in a short period of time or at least not in a job ready proficiency.

author: @DarkGT
text: Sadly I keep failing on my interviews. On the last one I failed because of my " soft skills" and "business acumen" . One tip I can share with the job seekers is to demand a feedback on your performance so you can know what you failed you during the interview process. The companies don't care about you, so it's very rare (at least in my experience) to get a feedback from an employer.

text: This is a great video and has got me excited to continue my journey as a new DA. author: @iAM2AM
text: Imagine a world where the tech industry has gotten so bloated that you can't even just apply for a job and submit a resume anymore. Step 1) Build your resume. Step 2) Don't include your life. Just the parts the recruiter cares about. Your experience outside of their concerns don't matter much. For in tech, you're not human. You're the product that makes the product. Step 3) Reach out to recruiters. Because being good at something isn't enough anymore. Thousands of people are good at things. Nowadays, you have to show a lot of things that have nothing to do with the job itself and only prove to exclude highly talented people who test and interview poorly but are more capable than the valedictorian extroverts they hire. Personality has nothing to do with work. At all. Ever. Work from home people proved that. Answering a bunch of non-sensacle questions in an interview with some egotistical hiring manager who asks stupid questions like: "You're stuck in a room with a green balloon and a red light. What do you do?"  At this point, I just interview to waste people's time. If I get it. Great. If not. So what. Ask me a dumb question? My response is always the same: "Make fun of you for asking a stupid question that has nothing to do with this interview or the job I applied for. That's step one. Step two: Pop the balloon. Next question please."

text: I've watched a lot of your videos and I appreciate the information! üòä  After going through the Google Data Analyst career cert and completing the case study I realized how difficult it was to clean a huge data set without being able to see every single line of data. That said, do you have any course suggestions that primarily focus on cleaning data without using Excel to physically scroll through every line-entry?  In the Google case-study example, you receive multiple data-sets that had a lot of commonalities, but also A LOT of differences. My attempt was to try and combine all of the data-sets into one massive data-set where I either removed inconsistent columns or would try to make data-points exist by extracting information from related columns. With about 6gb of data I find it extremely hard to believe that I just so happened to have stumbled across all data-integrity issues with R and PostgreSQL, and the dataset was too massive to review every single line in Excel üòï.
